## MCP Threat Model Summary

This MCP server is designed to defend against the following MCP-specific threats. Full details are in [`docs/security/threat-model.md`](docs/security/threat-model.md).

### Tool Poisoning
Tool descriptions are loaded at connect time and injected into the LLM context. We prevent poisoning by:
- Tool descriptions are static strings defined in source code; no user-supplied content is interpolated
- All tool inputs validated against strict immutable Zod/JSON Schema
- Egress from tool execution limited to an explicit allowlist of approved domains

### Prompt Injection
Adversarial instructions may arrive via tool input parameters or external API responses used as tool results. We mitigate by:
- Treating all tool response content as untrusted data; never interpolating it directly into system prompts
- Validating all tool inputs via `ValidationPipe` before processing

### OAuth Token Audience Enforcement
Per the MCP specification (2025-11-25), **token passthrough is forbidden**. This server:
- Validates the `aud` (audience) claim on every inbound Bearer token
- Rejects tokens where `aud` does not match this server's registered resource identifier
- Implements RFC 8707 Resource Indicators; does not accept ambient credentials

### Confused-Deputy Prevention
This server acts as an OAuth Resource Server only and never forwards tokens to downstream services. For proxy configurations: per-client consent is enforced; redirect URIs are matched exactly.

### Developer Tooling
MCP Inspector and other developer tooling must be run authenticated and on a non-public port. Upgrade to MCP Inspector ≥0.14.1 (fixes CVE-2025-49596, CVSS 9.4).

